An American crony capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the US Department of Finance and its IMF allies shifted the blame for the problems of this region to crony capitalism, a lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, use American accounting control firms, and introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed faster than any other region - and with greater stability - over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "One must be faultless to criticize others".
Enron used complex accounting strategies and financial products (derivatives) to deceive investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to acquire influence and power, shape US energy policy, and evade regulations.
Crony capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of one party.
The former US Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, would have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on behalf of Enron in the contentious conflict in India.
When in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards board attempted to clean up the accounting of executive compensation.
It was partly due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was thwarted.
The American enthusiasm to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is just a thin veil for the well-being of old businesses: giving favors to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed is evidence of the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it is evidence of the importance of a free press that can not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted Enron money was revealed.
The campaign contributions were not just a matter of public interest, but an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything went well in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this company.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be made public.
The democracies are undermined by corporate interests that can in fact buy elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons concern the economy, particularly the information economy.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals to be provided to efficiently allocate resources, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The auditing process is meant to put limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians?
Who will control the auditors?
We rely heavily on motivations.
The auditors want to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between consulting and auditing practices brings other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within auditing firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the controls could be compromised.
He is probably the unsung hero of the debacle.
But auditing firms and their corporate clients - which is not surprising, given the cabal that developed - vigorously attacked his proposal to separate consulting and auditing activities.
What Levitt understood - and what the Enron debacle has so clearly shown - is that motivations are important, but that unregulated markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
Markets cannot provide motivations for wealth creation; they can provide motivations for the type of combinations that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new complex financial instruments - highlights the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make it easier to complicate them.
Instead of facing the problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American crony capitalism.
The major problem of our time is finding the right balance between government and market.
The status quo will claim that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But most of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act similarly.
They are right - and that is exactly the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received reflects the company's economic situation sufficiently.
Under the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot count on them when so many people around the world see nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we find that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of such abuses becomes apparent, new areas for abuse are created time and time again - take the US repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial and investment activities.
We have repeatedly seen the consequences of the excesses of unbridled market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to swing to the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
